echo "Let's test what happens if I change: "
echo "onOffsetChange(offsetX + panChange.x, offsetY + panChange.y)"
echo "Will it drag the PDF properly in vertical direction when zoomed in?"
echo "If we allow vertical pan (offsetY + panChange.y), then users can drag the page around when zoomed in. BUT wait, if they pan down too much, they'll see white space. However, users can also scroll the LazyColumn."
echo "Actually, if \`LazyColumn\` is handling scroll, and we add \`panChange.y\` to \`offsetY\`, we are double-scrolling if LazyColumn ALSO scrolls."
echo "Wait, when \`transformable\` is active (which requires two fingers usually? No, \`transformable\` handles two-finger gestures. Panning with ONE finger is NOT handled by \`transformable\`!!! Panning with ONE finger is handled by \`scroll\` (LazyColumn) or \`pointerInput\`!)"
echo "Wait! \`transformable\` in Compose only detects TWO-finger pan/zoom!"
echo "If you zoom in and try to pan with ONE finger, \`transformable\` doesn't do anything for one finger, EXCEPT if you are already using two fingers. Wait, \`transformable\` CAN handle one finger pan? No, \`detectTransformGestures\` is two fingers."
echo "Wait, the code uses \`rememberTransformableState\` and \`Modifier.transformable\`. Modifier.transformable handles zooming and panning, but usually panning requires TWO fingers! If the user uses ONE finger to drag, it goes to LazyColumn."
echo "However, if the user zooms in (scale > 1f), dragging the LazyColumn with one finger will SCROLL the LazyColumn. BUT wait, the issue says 'cant drag pdf properly in vertical direction'. If scale > 1f, scrolling the LazyColumn scrolls the ITEMS vertically. But the problem is that \`graphicsLayer { scaleY = scale; translationY = offsetY }\` means that the items are scaled around the CENTER. If you scroll the LazyColumn, it might jump, or you can't reach the edges of the scaled page!"
echo "Ah! If you scale a LazyColumn, its layout bounds are STILL the unscaled bounds! So it clips or you can't scroll to the edges of the zoomed page, because LazyColumn only scrolls until the unscaled item reaches the edge!"
echo "If scale is 3x, the page is 3x larger. But LazyColumn thinks the page is 1x size. So when you scroll to the 'top' of the LazyColumn, the top of the 1x page is at the top of the screen. BUT because of the 3x scale from the center, the top of the page is now way OFF SCREEN! And you CANNOT scroll any further up because LazyColumn thinks you are already at the top!"
echo "Yes! This is the classic Compose zoom issue on LazyColumn. If you apply scale to the entire LazyColumn, the scroll bounds don't change. So you cannot pan vertically to see the top/bottom edges of the zoomed content using LazyColumn scroll."
